<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- Section A (bars 1-12): Standard F major I-IV-V-vi progressions. LH at half-note rhythm throughout
  to contrast with moving melody. Per-chord changes at quarter-note level only when multiple chords
  per bar (bars 1, 3, 4). Bars 6 and 12 use "43" / ①Δ for sustained-chord variety.
- Bar 7 RH raised an octave (C5-F5) to differentiate the repeat from bars 1-6.
- Section B (bars 13-19): New material. Bar 18 has chromatic melody B-natural passing through;
  LH keeps diatonic vii°(E°) below. Bar 19 opens with 2-beat silence — the biggest textural gap.
- Section C (bars 20-32): Tonal excursion through Gm/Bb area. Bars 21-25 emphasize ii(Gm) in
  various inversions and whole-note durations to evoke the modal gravity of the chorale text.
  Eb sub as IV(Bb), Cm sub as ii(Gm), G major sub as ii(Gm) — all nearest diatonic equivalents.
- Bar 30 (climax): fastest harmonic rhythm in piece (all 4 beats distinct chords), vi-V-I-IV.
- Final cadence: IΔ-style return (bar 32 whole I).

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- Section C LH bass line: F2→G2→Bb2→G2→D2→F2→D2→G2→A2→C2→F2 — stepwise and 3rd motion dominates.
- Bar 18: vi-vii°-V inner voice E4 sustained across all 3 beats (common tone).
- Bar 30: Bass line D2-C2-F2-Bb2 = all stepwise descending root motion (cycle of 5ths rhythm).
- Common tone F3 in LH bridges I-IV alternations throughout (bars 1,3,4,5,15,16).

TEXTURE ARC:
- Section A: sparse and steady, establishing harp texture. Bars 6/12 provide breath via sustained chord.
- Section B: bar 19 2-beat rest is the structural hinge — pivot before Section C.
- Section C: builds through Gm area to bar 30 per-beat climax, then descends to final I.
- 32 bars total, arc: sparse→growing→breath→excursion→climax→cadence.
-->
